Contents

Today we will be simulating paths of the Wiener Process (aka Standard Brownian Motion), Generalized Wiener Process (aka Brownian Motion), and performing related visualizations in Rpackage ggplot2: visualization of a path (for a given \(\omega\)) and visualization of the distribution (for a given \(t\)). While doing so, we will learn about data.frames and how to manipulate them. We will also see how to save images and how to use loops and write functions. Follow the links/resources on Moodle to learn more.

Exercise 1

Simulate one path of the Wiener Process on the interval \([0,0.5]\) with a time-step of 0.001 (process starts at 0) and then plot it.

#solution with a 'for' loop (syntax: for(var in seq) { expr }) 

TT<-0.5 #assign 0.5 to the Rvariable 'TT'
dt<-0.001 #assign 0.001 to the Rvariable 'dt'
tt<-seq(from=0,to=TT,by=dt) #create a sequence 0,0.001,...,0.5 
                            #and assign it to the Rvariable 'tt'
head(tt) #show the top of 'tt'
## [1] 0.000 0.001 0.002 0.003 0.004 0.005
zz<-rep(x=NA,times=length(tt)) #create a sequence of NA's of the same length as 'tt'
                             #and assign it to the Rvariable 'zz'
head(zz)                             
## [1] NA NA NA NA NA NA
zz[1]<-0 #to the first slot of 'zz', assign 0
head(zz)
## [1]  0 NA NA NA NA NA
#'for' loop indexed by Rvariable 'i' with values in the sequence 2,3,...,length(zz)
for(i in 2:length(zz)) 
{#opening brace of the 'for' loop's instructions
  zz[i]<-zz[i-1]+sqrt(dt)*rnorm(n=1,mean=0,sd=1)
  #to the ith slot of 'zz', assign:
  #the value from the previous slot 
  #plus
  #one N(0,1) random variable multiplied by 'sqrt(dt)' 
}#closing brace of the 'for' loop's instructions
head(zz)
## [1]  0.000000000 -0.006353274  0.016436533  0.004757768 -0.041777269
## [6] -0.017874552
plot(x=tt,y=zz,type='l') #plot 'zz' versus 'tt' using 'line' (l=line)

To perform the same task(s) in other programming languages would require similar sort of commands.

#loop-free solution

#'TT', 'dt', 'tt' already declared
head(tt)
## [1] 0.000 0.001 0.002 0.003 0.004 0.005
zz<-cumsum(c(0,sqrt(dt)*rnorm(n=length(tt)-1,mean=0,sd=1))) 
#this over-writes 'zz' from the earlier chunk of code
head(zz) 
## [1] 0.00000000 0.03676111 0.09353102 0.06406283 0.06280389 0.13081621
plot(x=tt,y=zz,type='l')

The loop-free code is more R-specific. Why are the two paths different?

#'tt', 'zz' already declared

wp1<-data.frame(time=tt,value=zz)

wp<-rbind(wp1,wp2)
ggplot(data=wp,aes(x=time,y=value,col=rep))+geom_line()

Exercise 6

More efficiency/automation: use for loop to create data.frame wp of the previous exercise.

#'TT', 'dt', 'tt' already declared

wp<-NULL
#'NULL' is a reserved word in R
# create/prepare an Rvariable 'wp' (with a 'NULL' value) 
# for collecting/appending all the paths
for(rr in 1:2)
{
  zz<-cumsum(c(0,sqrt(dt)*rnorm(n=length(tt)-1,mean=0,sd=1)))

  temp<-data.frame(time=tt,value=zz,rep=paste(rr))
  #create an auxilary/temporary data frame and assign it to an Rvariable 'temp'  

  wp<-rbind(wp,temp)
  #append (row-wise) the auxilary/temporary data frame to the Rvariable 'wp'
  #and update 'wp'
}
str(wp)

Exercise 7

Even more efficiency/automation: write a user-defined Rfunction called WP which for a given interval \([0,T]\) and time-step \(\Delta t\) will simulate \(R\) paths of the Wiener Process and will return a data.frame with all the paths, tagging the paths with the path/replication index (in string/character format). The input arguments should be: TT, dt, RR. Clear the workspace before you begin. Read about function in R, eg, at https://www.datamentor.io/r-programming/function/ or https://www.statmethods.net/management/userfunctions.html

rm(list=ls())#clear the workspace

#syntax for an Rfunction called 'WP'
#with arguments TT,dt,RR
#(there are no default values for the arguments); 
#purpose: 
#to generate RR (tagged) paths of the 
#Wiener Process on [0,TT]
#input:
#TT: [num] end point of the time interval [0,TT]
#dt: [num] time increment to discretize [0,TT]
#RR: [int] number of paths
#output: data.frame (with three variables/columns) 
#        with RR tagged paths  

WP<-function(TT,dt,RR)
{#opening brace of the Rfunction
  tt<-seq(from=0,to=TT,by=dt)
  result<-NULL 
  for(rr in 1:RR)
  {
    zz<-cumsum(c(0,sqrt(dt)*rnorm(n=length(tt)-1))) 
    temp<-data.frame(time=tt,value=zz,rep=paste(rr)) 
    result<-rbind(result,temp) 
  } 
  return(result)
  #return the Rvariable 'result' as the value of the Rfunction
}#closing brace of the Rfunction

Rvariables used inside the function are defined locally, i.e., not accessible outside it. Test it. What is the benefit of declaring an Rfunction? We dropped mean and sd arguments from Rfunction rnorm. By doing so, we assume that these arguments take on the default values, which in this case are 0 and 1, respectively. If you declare WP()
without default values for its arguments, executing WP() will produce an error. What happens if you execute WP (no paretheses)?

Exercise 8

Use your function to obtain a data.frame with 100 paths of the Standard Brownian Motion on \([0,1.5]\). Use time increment of 0.001. Plot all the paths using ggplot Rfunction. Use different colours to distinguish between different paths, but do not display the legend.

output<-WP(TT=1.5,dt=0.001,RR=100)#correction here
gg<-ggplot(data=output,aes(x=time,y=value,col=rep))+geom_line()
gg<-gg+theme(legend.position='none')
print(gg)

           aes(x=value))

                      fill='red',col='black',size=2)

Exercise 12

Simulate one path of the Generalized Wiener Process (Rvariable xx) with a drift \(a=-0.01\) and diffusion \(b=0.02\) on the interval \([0,0.5]\) with a time-step of 0.001 (process starts at \(x_0=0\) by default). Store tt and xx as a data.frame using some useful tagging. Plot xx versus tt using ggplot.

#'TT', 'dt', 'tt' need to be declared first
# we declare them again as we cleared the workspace

TT<-0.5 #assign 0.5 to the Rvariable 'TT'
dt<-0.001 #assign 0.001 to the Rvariable 'dt'
tt<-seq(from=0,to=TT,by=dt) #create a sequence 0,0.001,...,0.5 
                            #and assign it to the Rvariable 'tt'

aa<- -0.01
bb<-0.02
rr<-1#replicate 1
xx<-cumsum(c(0,aa*dt+bb*sqrt(dt)*rnorm(n=length(tt)-1)))
temp<-data.frame(time=tt,value=xx,rep=paste(rr), 
                 drift=paste(aa),diffusion=paste(bb))
ggplot(data=temp,aes(x=time,y=value))+geom_line()
